Habana Vieja, or ‚ÄúOld Havana‚Äù was my favorite part of Cuba‚Äôs capital! The colorful old cars, the classic architecture, music in the streets. üá®üá∫
‚Äî
In recent years, Cuba has seen major changes as Americans began flooding in when the rules were relaxed. Its been a mixed blessing. Local people are able to earn more from the tourism, but it‚Äôs been so sudden that the whole country was running out of things like beer. üò≥
‚Äî
If you‚Äôre planning a trip to Cuba this year, make sure to check out my favorite things to do in Havana! New blog post, ‚úÖLINKED IN BIO‚úÖ.

node.text:
One of the most common questions I get via email is: how did I fund my first backpacking trip all those years ago? How could I afford to travel long-term before my blog made any money? üí∏
‚Äî
Well, before I started traveling, while I was working a normal day job, I also had a ‚Äúside-hustle‚Äù writing and selling a couple of ebooks online. It was this extra income that helped me fund that first year of travel adventures! üåé
‚Äî
This isn‚Äôt the only way to earn some extra money on the side though. Watching cats & dogs. Renting out your car. Dressing up like Jesus. Selling blood plasma. Freelance bookkeeping. Assembling furniture. Running local tours. There are MANY ways if you think outside the box!
‚Äî
Go check out my latest blog post, ‚úÖ LINKED IN BIO ‚úÖ, to read about 38 creative ways to make some extra money this year.
‚Äî
Do you have any side-hustles for earning extra money? üí≤

HAPPY 2019! ü•≥ WHAT ARE YOUR PLANS THIS YEAR?
-
These were my 9 most popular photos in 2018. ‚û°Ô∏è SWIPE TO SEE THEM ALL!
-
It‚Äôs been a crazy year, with a lot of changes! Anna & I are expecting a baby boy in the spring! We moved from California to Texas, then on to Italy to prepare for the new addition to our family. üë∂
-
I sincerely want to thank everyone who‚Äôs been following. Whether you‚Äôre here for the travel tips, photo inspiration, or just interested in learning about our nomadic lifestyle. Your comments and emails keep me motivated to continue sharing here and on the blog! üëçüèº
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
‚≠êÔ∏èMY TOP 9 PHOTOS‚≠êÔ∏è
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
1. One of my favorite adventures with Anna was this road trip through Morocco, including the beautiful blue city of Chefchaouen.

2. Bertha! My beloved Jeep Rubicon. I sold her before we moved to Italy, but had a lot of fun first, including this trip to the Alabama Hills in California.

3. Just standing on a giant gorilla skull in Hawaii! It‚Äôs an awesome movie prop from KONG: SKULL ISLAND on Kualoa Ranch.

4. A pretty sunset at El Matador Beach in Malibu, California.

5. Lucky timing as the sun breaks through storm clouds at St. Colman‚Äôs Cathedral in Cobh, Ireland.

6. Morocco again. This time wandering the colorful street markets of Marrakech.

7. Our epic doors-off helicopter flight over the Na-Pali coastline on Kauai. So much fun!

This is #Kamchatka, a 900-mile long Russian peninsula attached to Siberia that juts out into the Pacific Ocean. It‚Äôs about the size of California, with only 400,000 residents.
-
Kamchatka is a wilderness playground, composed of thick boreal forests, geothermically active volcanoes, and barren alpine tundra landscapes like this. It was off-limits to outsiders until the 1990s, due to its strategic importance to the Soviet military (nuclear submarine bases).
-
Read my new blog post ‚≠êÔ∏è(LINKED IN BIO)‚≠êÔ∏è to learn more about our snowmobile adventure here! ‚û°Ô∏è

The Colosseum! One of the new 7 wonders of the world.
-
Rome‚Äôs most famous building once held 80,000 spectators for deadly battles between wild animals & gladiators. ü¶Åüêªüêä‚öîÔ∏è
-
There was a saying: ‚Äúbread & circuses‚Äù keep the people happy. The games kept the Roman population distracted from reality - and political involvement. ü•ñüé™

Kamchatka! Russia‚Äôs land of volcanoes. üåã
-
This is the city of Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, the main city on this remote peninsula in Russia‚Äôs far-east.
-
From here we bussed to the interior, then hopped on snowmobiles to visit ethnic Even reindeer herders and learn about their way of life in the wilderness. It was such a wild trip!

It‚Äôs a #WhiteReindeer invasion! I found this guy in the Far Eastern Siberian wilderness of Kamchatka, Russia. He wasn‚Äôt so friendly... and let me know it. üòù
-
Inspired by @mads viral shot earlier this week. üéÑ ü¶å

No one truly knows why the Maya civilization collapsed.
-
Some think it was due to over-population and lack of sustainable resources.
-
Others believe it was constant warfare that led to a breakdown into chaos.
-
A third theory is that a long dry-spell killed their harvests.
-
Then Spanish invaders helped finish them off.
-
All we have left is the ruins of their impressive cities... I really hope modern humanity doesn‚Äôt succumb to the same fate. üóø

This is Verona, Italy. Our new home-base for the next few years. üáÆüáπ
-
I‚Äôve been asked why we moved here:
-
‚Ä¢ The food is amazing!
‚Ä¢ It‚Äôs very affordable
‚Ä¢ Slow paced lifestyle
‚Ä¢ Universal health system
‚Ä¢ High-speed trains
‚Ä¢ Easy access to the rest of Europe (cheap flights!)
‚Ä¢ Dolomites are only an hour or two away üèî
‚Ä¢ Family friendly & low crime üë∂
‚Ä¢ Amazon Prime works!
‚Ä¢ Fiber internet available
‚Ä¢ Pet friendly (we can take @poofythefluffycat to restaurants!)
‚Ä¢ Larger cities like Milan & Venice nearby
‚Ä¢ Mild climate
‚Ä¢ Regional airport for Europe, train to Milan for overseas flights
‚Ä¢ Tons of culture & things to do!

So that‚Äôs the gist. We had other areas in mind, but this seemed to be the best compromise for us both, and our different tastes. I wanted easy access to big mountains, @anna.everywhere didn‚Äôt want to live in a small town. üëçüèº
-
Just posted a quick walk-through of our new apartment on IG Stories if you wanna check it out! ‚úÖ

Once you get past the army of vendors at the entrance, ancient stone carvings of fearsome creatures and bloodthirsty warriors at #ChichenItza inspire awe and trigger unease at the same time.
-
The ruins are extensive, covering 740 acres. Many sections have still never been excavated. While wandering around the massive archaeological site, I kept wondering what hidden treasures lay undiscovered beneath my feet‚Ä¶
-
Read my new blog post ‚úÖLINKED IN BIO‚úÖ to learn what you need to know before visiting this amazing place!

Just chillin‚Äô with my new furry Russian friends... ü¶å
-

Early morning photography session in Iceland. üì∑ Getting out into nature with my camera on a regular basis helps recharge my soul. üèî
-
Much of my job entails sitting in front of a computer for hours each day, but it‚Äôs these adventures outside in beautiful exotic locations around the world that makes it all worthwhile!
-
‚Ä¢ Camera: @sonyalpha #A7RIII (photo taken with my backup #A6500)

Of the many religious buildings I‚Äôve visited around the world, #Hallgrimskirkja in Iceland is one of the most memorable. It really embodies Icelandic minimalist design and was modeled after their rugged landscape of mountains & glaciers.
-
I definitely recommend paying the extra fee to take an elevator to the top for a colorful birds-eye-view of Reykjav√≠k too!

Kalalau Beach is one of the most beautiful places in Hawaii.
-
The only way to reach it is a sketchy 11 mile hike in, or by sea kayak.
-
The Kalalau Trail has been on my bucket-list for years, but a series of landslides blocked access during our visit to Kauai with @hawaiianairlines. I‚Äôll just have to return!
-
Would you go camping here? ‚õ∫Ô∏èüå¥
-

This is why Kauai is called the ‚Äúgarden island‚Äù. Staring down from an open-door helicopter at Manawaiopuna Falls cascading 400 feet into the river below. Our pilot banked sharply to the side so all that was keeping me from falling out was the harness. What a rush! üöÅ
-
Sometimes the waterfall is also called ‚ÄúJurassic Falls‚Äù due to its prominence in the original Jurassic Park movie. A place so remote that the only way to reach it is by helicopter.
-
Anyone afraid of heights? Or flying? Or both? Because this was one wild ride! üò≥

Anna & I had a wonderful time island-hopping between Oahu & Kauai in Hawaii with @hawaiianairlines for the re-launch of their Hawaiian Airlines World Elite Mastercard.

We hit the waves, did some cliff jumping, and ate more poke than I thought was humanly possible! üèÑüèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

SURPRISE! @anna.everywhere and I are moving to Italy next month! üáÆüáπ @PoofyTheFluffyCat is coming too. üêà
-
We‚Äôve decided on the Northern Italian city of #Verona, after visiting earlier this year. We tried Colorado, California, and Texas, but just didn‚Äôt find what we were looking for in the States. So now we‚Äôre off to give Italy a go!
-
We both have EU passports (I have dual citizenship in Ireland now) and we both work online, which makes moving to Europe possible. We picked Verona because it‚Äôs a pretty town that‚Äôs not too big but not too small, a short train ride away from larger cities, and very close to the Italian Dolomites, some of the best mountains in Europe.
-
So it‚Äôs back to being an expat for a while! I guess I‚Äôll have to start learning Italian... ü§ì

The Scottish capital of Edinburgh is one of my favorite cities in Europe! Medieval architecture, dark alleyways, and a dramatic twisted history. No wonder so many writers have been inspired here...
-
But Edinburgh has also become a vibrant hub of art and theatre, with great festivals taking over the world stage.
-
Plus Whisky tasting? Ghost hunting? Deep Fried Mars Bars? This city has everything!
-
Check out my new blog post for tips on all my favorite things to do in Edinburgh. Linked in bio. üëçüèº
Middle-Earth, Iceland

There‚Äôs a reason why it‚Äôs called ‚Äúthe land of fire & ice‚Äù. üåã‚ùÑÔ∏è
-
üöÅ @djiglobal #mavic2pro

It‚Äôs official. I‚Äôm an Irish Citizen now! ‚òòÔ∏è
-
This past year I went through the legal process of obtaining Irish citizenship. Because my Grandmother was born in Ireland, I was able to claim citizenship by descent through a special law. It took about 9 months, and cost about $700.
-
As a dual citizen of the United States and Ireland, with two passports, I can now travel or live in the European Union without restrictions.
-
Did you know that about 40 million Americans have Irish ancestry? Many of their ancestors traveled to the United States from the port city of Cobh, pictured here, looking for a better life abroad.
-
Now more and more American/British citizens are applying for Irish Citizenship, as a hedge against the craziness and ultra-nationalism going on in the world. Giving themselves another option, just in case. üåé
-
If you‚Äôre interested in reading about how I became a dual citizen of Ireland, check out my new blog post, linked in the bio. üëçüèº
-
Anyone else have dual citizenship somewhere?

Kerlingarfj√∂ll is one of the most spectacular geothermal areas in Iceland. Located deep in the highlands, it vividly shows the contrast between the "fire & ice" that Iceland is known for.
-
There are many bubbling hot springs that dot the red/orange landscape, enveloping the whole area with steam.
-
Icelandic legend says this is the home of a mysterious troll woman, who was turned to stone while returning home after dark! üëπ
-
üì∑ F8 | 1/250 sec | ISO 250
-
Self-portrait using a tripod and intervalometer to shoot images every 5 seconds (which allowed me to hike out, pose, then hike back to retrieve the camera and choose the best shot.)

Commuting to work in #Iceland! üòú
-
Many of Iceland‚Äôs ‚ÄúF-Roads‚Äù contain river crossings like this one. You need to be VERY careful attempting them, even in a 4x4.
-
Some are too deep for normal trucks, and people have been killed getting caught in fast moving glacial rivers.
-
Before attempting a river crossing, you should either walk the river yourself, or watch another vehicle cross first. And know your vehicle‚Äôs capabilities.
-
Drive slow & steady ‚Äî don‚Äôt splash in too fast or you could drown your engine...
-
Most car rental companies don‚Äôt include insurance for this kind of travel, so you need to be prepared for the consequences if you fuck up!
-
As long as you‚Äôre safe about it, it‚Äôs a fun way to get off the beaten path. üëçüèº

Got a lot of questions about my Afghanistan trip after the last post.
-
Yes, you can travel to Afghanistan. Women too, although I‚Äôm not sure I‚Äôd recommended it alone.
-
No, I don‚Äôt recommend it solo for most people. It‚Äôs what I‚Äôd call a ‚Äúblack diamond‚Äù destination. Like how they rate ski slopes. You need to work your way up to it.
-
This is a trip I‚Äôd been planning for years. Following local news. Tracking down obscure trip reports. Talking to others who‚Äôd been recently.
-
For example, the border between Tajikistan & Afghanistan sometimes closes without warning. For days, or weeks. Which would leave you stranded, as the road to Kabul is too dangerous.
-
The Taliban is only 20 miles away. Last year, they captured the border town area (that I entered from) for 2 weeks before being kicked out again.
-
The Wakhi people, like this man, were very welcoming and friendly. However there are less nice people not far away. The situation is constantly changing.
-
And travel in Afghanistan is tough. Just getting to the start of my trek took 2 days of driving through deserts and rivers with multiple breakdowns. Meals were basically flat bread, warm sour yak yogurt, and if you‚Äôre lucky, some goat.
-
Just wanted to share a bit behind the scenes for what went into this trip!
-
There are a few adventure tour groups that visit the Wakhan (check Google) which would make things easier. I passed one of them as I was leaving the mountains. The region does see about 100 tourists every year.

The ancient tomb of an Afghan tribal leader and his family, decorated with Ibex horns and red cloth flapping in the wind.
-
Trekking 100 miles through the mountains of #Afghanistan was one of my most memorable adventures to date! If you‚Äôd like to see more photos from this trip, go visit my blog ExpertVagabond.com
-
Wakhan Corridor, Afghanistan

Bar hopping in the streets of Ireland! üç∫ (Galway)

I traveled to Ireland with my family a few years ago to track down the old home of my Irish grandmother, and learn about our ancestry. It was a very cool experience.
-
I‚Äôm certainly not the only American with Irish roots, so if you‚Äôre planning a trip of your own, make sure to check out my new blog post where I share some of the best things to do in #Dublin. Link in my bio!
-
What‚Äôs the first thing that comes to mind when you think of Ireland? Leprechauns? Whiskey? Music? üçÄ

Tre Cime di Lavaredo is one of the most iconic hikes in the Italian Dolomites. It‚Äôs a pretty easy 6 mile loop with incredible views, but not much elevation gain.
-
Italian authorities have started restricting vehicle traffic into the Dolomites during summer months at Sella Pass, allowing only 350 cars per day (previously up to 5000 cars a day made the trip). It‚Äôs a new attempt to curb the massive amount of day-tripping tourism, and help save their stunning environment.
-
However local restaurant and hotel owners are upset, complaining it will drastically reduce their income, and visitors will simply use a different mountain pass, sending the tourism dollars to other areas. It just goes to show there are no easy answers to solving this problem!
-
üì∑ @anna.everywhere

#sustainabletravel #dolomites

Is Instagram & #SocialMedia ruining travel?
-
The massive growth of social media and travel blogs in recent years has had a profound impact on how we travel. Not all of it positive. As someone who makes a living inspiring others to travel, this topic has been on my mind a lot lately.
-
I think overcrowding and bad behavior have always been a part of the travel experience. But a combination of population growth, a larger worldwide middle-class, the explosion of digital photography, and efficient social media tools for expressing our already narcissistic nature are making things worse. What do you think?
-
Check out my new blog post to learn more. Linked in my bio. üëçüèº

Greetings from #Austin! If you missed my last post, Anna and I have decided to move here for a few months. It‚Äôs one of the perks of location independence‚Ä¶ moving to a new city/state/country just for fun. üòú
-
It‚Äôs only been a few days, but I‚Äôm starting to see why everyone loves this town. Great food, friendly people, tons of music, and a fun attitude. üé∏
-
We‚Äôll both be presenting @travel_con (a cool travel industry conference) here next month -- I‚Äôm leading some photo walks and Anna is talking about Instagram. If you‚Äôre going to be around, let us know!

#TrueAustin #StreetArt

Goodbye California, hello Texas!
-
After a year of living in Los Angeles, @anna.everywhere & I have decided to move on. While I was surprised at just how much I ended up enjoying LA, we've decided it‚Äôs just not for us long-term. It‚Äôs a bit too crowded, a bit too expensive, and a bit too dry.
-
So we‚Äôre hitting the road again, this time for a temporary move to #Austin, Texas. We‚Äôll be there for a few months before moving on to our ultimate destination, which I‚Äôll keep secret for now (just for fun). üòé
-
I thought I‚Äôd be able to slow down and plant some roots somewhere, but we seem to just keep moving regardless. Maybe this is the curse of being nomadic. That after moving so much, over so many years ‚Äî what‚Äôs the big deal with moving once more? I guess moving once a year is better than once every few months, so there‚Äôs still hope!
-
Anyone have tips they want to share about Austin? I hear we need to try some BBQ... ü•©

Morocco‚Äôs Blue Pearl, the ancient city of #Chefchaouen. üá≤üá¶
-
This is the view from an old Spanish mosque on the mountainside above. From here you can see the ‚Äúblue city‚Äù is really blue & white!

Welcome to the Grand Canyon of the Pacific! Waimea Canyon on the island of #Kauai is 10 miles long, and up to 3000 feet deep. Can you believe this is Hawaii?!
-
The colorful mix of red volcanic earth and green jungle is really impressive to see in person. Not to mention all the waterfalls‚Ä¶ had a lot of fun hiking around here capturing images of this landscape. üòé

Is this the most beautiful place in the world? The steep emerald-green cliffs of Kauai's Na Pali Coast will take your breath away! Massive waterfalls, pristine beaches, and lush tropical valleys. It‚Äôs basically the definition of ‚Äúisland paradise‚Äù. üå¥
-
The only way to experience this 17 mile stretch of rugged coastline is by hiking the Kalalau Trail (unfortunately it was closed due to landslides during our visit), by boat, sea kayak, or helicopter. I‚Äôm still buzzing on adrenaline from this open-door helo flight...

I love getting up early in the morning for colorful sunrise light! This is a remote mountain cabin used by Even reindeer herders in the mountains of Kamchatka, Russia.

Craziest day ever. Traveled 60km over one of Kamchatka‚Äôs icy high plateaus. Battling 60mph winds. -39F wind chill. 
We were forced to evacuate back to the village of Esso for a night, as we wouldn‚Äôt have made it to the next reindeer camp before dark.

This is Nn‚Äôon‚Äôna of the Hadza tribe in Tanzania. The Hadza are one of the last true hunter/gatherer peoples on Earth, living basically the same way they have for the past 10,000 years. We tagged along for one of their early morning hunting trips, where they shot this dik dik and a pheasant-like bird. üèπ
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
Hadza men hunt twice a day to feed their village, using a quiver of different wooden arrows (including some with poison tips). They hunt birds, monkeys, antelope, and more. Anything they can get really. Women gather berries, fruit, and tubers. Families live in simple dome shelters made of branches, or inside giant hollowed-out baobab trees.
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
I know many people here might not be fans of hunting. I convinced my animal-loving wife @anna.everywhere to come along, but she wasn‚Äôt too excited watching the hunt. Anyway, I promise not to fill my Instagram feed with dead animals on a regular basis! This animal did not go to waste.
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
However this is one of the reasons why I travel. To get out of my comfort zone. Experience culture shock. Understand how other people on our planet actually live, even if you don‚Äôt like what you see. You don‚Äôt have to like it ‚Äî just learn something new.
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
The Hadza live in the middle of the wilderness as bushmen. There are no supermarkets. No hip acai bowl cafes. No opportunities to earn money other than showing occasional tourists like us around.
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
I‚Äôll be sharing more about the Hadza people on my blog in the future. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
#Hadza #Hadzabe #Tanzania #Hunting @SoulOfTanzania

They mark their territory with their ‚Äútears‚Äù from that black spot at the corner of their eye. How cute are these things?! ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

A big part of my @canadabydesign self-drive road trip was experiencing some of BC‚Äôs indigenous First Nations culture. 
For 67 years the Canadian government tried to ban ‚Äúpotlatches‚Äù, a traditional way tribes met to self-govern themselves, celebrate, morn, and conduct business.

Sheer Chai (salty milk tea) is very important in the mountains of #Afghanistan. Made with black tea, goat/yak milk, and rock salt. Salt helps prevent dehydration at high altitudes.
Fresh early-morning snow covers a yurt in the Kyrgyz nomad community of Kashch Goz. There are about 1400 Kyrgyz people living in #Afghanistan's Wakhan Corridor.
The Mazar (sacred shrine) of Khajahbigali in the Afghan Wakhan. These ibex horn decorated rock tombs hold the skeletal remains of an old and powerful afghan family. #Afghanistan
Afghan hospitality is no joke! This is Arbab Pana. He slaughtered a goat for dinner, then provided me with a stone hut, blankets, and a yak-dung fire to keep warm during the night. #afghanistan
Abandoned stone shelter along #Afghanistan's Wakhan Corridor. Part of the 2,000 year old "silk road" caravan route. Can you imagine what it must have been like back then?

I'm back! Trekking over 100 miles through the rugged mountains of #Afghanistan's Wakhan Corridor in the footsteps of Marco Polo & Alexander the Great has been my most challenging & rewarding travel experience to date.

After 5 years of traveling the world I‚Äôve met some extraordinary people who‚Äôve inspired or guided me during this amazing journey. Continuing my partnership with @AmericanExpress, I‚Äôm sharing their stories with you.

Like the story of Fleming & Ellen, a pair of Journeymakers I met traveling through Greenland.

While trekking for 10 days across the Arctic Circle Trail, I unexpectedly met them at a remote wilderness cabin 50 miles from civilization.

We chatted for a few hours waiting for the steady rain outside to subside.

At 70 years old, they‚Äôve hiked the 100 mile long Arctic Circle Trail 6 times now. They've also spent a month trekking completely across Greenland‚Äôs vast ice cap, pulling food & supplies on sleds‚Ä¶

If that wasn‚Äôt enough to impress, they‚Äôve both hiked to Everest Base Camp and climbed Mont Blanc (Europe‚Äôs highest mountain at 15,777 ft.). They didn‚Äôt even start trekking until their 40‚Äôs either!

Before we parted ways, these incredibly inspiring senior citizen adventurers gave me tips for crossing a deep river further ahead on the trail, and ideas for my next adventure.

Thanks to Fleming & Ellen, I will never feel too old to seek out challenging new travel experiences. 
If they can do it at 70, so can we all! ‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨

After 5 years traveling the world I‚Äôve met some extraordinary people who‚Äôve inspired or guided me during this amazing journey. I‚Äôm excited to be working with @AmericanExpress to share these special stories with you.

Like the story of Isaac, a Journeymaker from Panama. Isaac guided me through the mysterious wilderness of Darien National Park where no roads exist. Trekking deep into the rainforest in search of rare frogs, birds, and snakes.

Rather than pay for a guesthouse, he invited me to stay with his family. We went hand-line fishing in the rain and grilled our catch for dinner. Isaac gave me a unique glimpse of what life is like for the indigenous Kuna who call this area home. ‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨

Hidden within the cloud forests of Tenorio National Park, the magnificent bright blue Rio Celeste Waterfall will take your breath away.

The 45 minute hike sent me through a scenic canopy of trees alive with curious white-faced monkeys, bright red poison dart frogs, singing birds, and fluttering blue morpho butterflies.

I heard the roar of the waterfall before I saw it. Slipping and sliding down the muddy trail, I rounded a bend and suddenly froze‚Ä¶

I couldn‚Äôt believe my eyes. It looked like something out of a fairytale. This powerful river came crashing 60 feet down from the trees into a dazzling pool of turquoise water. ‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨‚ñ¨

Yesterday I was robbed in Hebron by 2 teenagers. One snatched the $150 Oakley's off my head while another tripped me when I tried to run after the first. My arms (and ego) are a bit bruised, but that's all.

Talal here spoke good English, and translated for me at the police station (the Palestinian cops offered me a flash-bang grenade for my trouble). The percentage of good people in this world far outnumbers the bad.
